Here's how to save/restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Save draft when app backgrounds
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel();
            if (vm is not null)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Restore draft when app returns
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel();
            if (vm is not null)
                vm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        };

        window.Destroying += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel();
            if (vm is not null)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        };

        return window;
    }

    private NoteViewModel? GetNoteViewModel()
    {
        if (Windows.FirstOrDefault()?.Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
            return vm;
        return null;
    }
}
```

**2. Your ViewModel (with `CommunityToolkit.Mvvm`):**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = string.Empty;
}
```

**3. Your XAML page:**

```xml
<Editor Text="{Binding DraftText}" Placeholder="Start typing..." />
```

### Key points

| Concern | Guidance |
|---------|----------|
| **Why `Stopped` not `Deactivated`?** | `Deactivated` fires for dialogs/split-screen — the app may never actually background. |
| **Why also `Destroying`?** | On Android, the back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`. |
| **Why `Preferences`?** | It's synchronous and fast — lifecycle handlers must complete in ~1–2 seconds to avoid ANR/watchdog kills. |
| **`Resumed` vs first launch** | `Resumed` only fires after `Stopped`, not on initial launch. Load your initial state in the ViewModel constructor or `OnAppearing`. |

For larger drafts (images, rich text), serialize to a file instead of `Preferences`, but keep the write fast.
